{code:borderStyle=solid}
progress (issue count) is not empty
{code}

This could be useful to show only the issue with this field filled out.

h3. Issue Summary

When using a Plan with multiple projects in its issue sources, if you have components with the same name but from different projects, grouping them together in the *View settings* will block you from creating issues under the component.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Have a Plan and add more than 1 project in the issue sources
# Create the same *Components* in 2 or more of these projects (eg. Housekeeping)
# In the *View settings* of your Plan, group by Component and add the different Housekeeping component into 1 group
# Create an issue right under a parent so it automatically takes the component
 
 !bug.png|thumbnail! 

h3. Expected Results

After saving the changes, this should create the issue under the parent and take the component value.

h3. Actual Results
*Changes couldn't be saved*
 !BUG_-_Advanced_Roadmaps_-_Jira.png|thumbnail! 

{code}
{"success":false,"error":{"error":"ISSUE_CREATE_EXCEPTION","errorMessages":[],"exception":{"type":"com.atlassian.rm.jpo.core.scenario.common.data.ScenarioCommitException","message":"Scenario commit error","stackTrace":[]}},"change":{"sequence":{}}}
{
    "success": false,
    "error": {
        "error": "ISSUE_CREATE_EXCEPTION",
        "errorMessages": [],
        "exception": {
            "type": "com.atlassian.rm.jpo.core.scenario.common.data.ScenarioCommitException",
            "message": "Scenario commit error",
            "stackTrace": []
        }
    },
    "change": {
        "sequence": {}
    }
}
{code}

h3. Workaround

The duplicate name components should be in separate groups, otherwise, there is no other known workaround for this behavior.

From documentation [Assign statuses and edit columns in a team managed project/|https://support.atlassian.com/jira-software-cloud/docs/assign-statuses-and-edit-columns-in-a-team-managed-project/], it is indicated  

{quote}For example, the _done_ status category must be in the rightmost column for its issues to be cleared from your board. If you have multiple done states, like _Won’t fix, Abandoned,_ and _All done_, you can assign them all to the rightmost column. Any issue moved to those three statuses will then be marked as resolved, and cleared from your board, if you use sprints.{quote}

This indicates how the last column will set the resolution of an issue, but considering that Team managed projects tend to be administered by people who may not be as familiar with Jira administration or the way boards work, it seems appropriate to provide additional messaging/tooltips to illustrate how the last column will affect issues, maybe an icon on the las column with an exclamation mark where you can see the message and/or link to the documentation would be helpful.

With the current pattern of *calculating the remaining days in a sprint*, Jira considers the following point:
 * Non-working days *will be disregarded*;
 * A current business day *is not considered*;
 * If you passed the time of the end date of the sprint, you'll also *disregard that day*;


1. Currently, within an Active Sprint, the sidebar button says "Remaining Days" but to add more clarity towards the calculation of Actual day Remaining for a Sprint, it would be more convenient if we replace the text "Remaining Days" with "Working days remaining"

Attached  !Screenshot 2021-05-19 at 12.22.40 PM.png|thumbnail! 

2. Another point to note is by default the time on the last day of the sprint is set 00:00 hrs, if we haven't set the time explicitly (I think most wouldn't) then the last day is effectively disregarded, so to avoid this miss, it would be nice to add a message such that the user can set the end date and time of the sprint accordingly.
